# Material verification

Drop this section verbatim into the root `CLAUDE.md` of your project (or
`AGENTS.md`, depending on which agent you use). No reasoning expected
from the agent — it's a contract of format for every factual claim.

```md
## Material verification

- Any claim of the type "build green / tests pass / CI green / drift
  detected / contact not found / OK" must be accompanied *in the same
  message* by the verification command and its raw output. Without that,
  the claim has no evidentiary value.
- Any number/count returned to a human must be verified by SQL query
  before being relayed.
- EXPLAIN ANALYZE on a production query: execute on the exact query the
  application code sends (view/RPC included), not on the target table
  in isolation. Run two consecutive runs before judging — the first
  may be a cold start.
- On 400/422 from an external partner (webhook, third-party API):
  demand the RAW payload before proposing a fix. No diagnosis on
  formatted form values.
- `tsc --noEmit` CLI = authority, IDE panel = potentially stale. Any
  critical IDE diagnostic appearing without obvious cause must be
  validated by `tsc` first.
```

## Why it works

The rule doesn't ask the agent to reason better — it asks the agent to
attach material to the assertion. An assertion attached to an artefact
the human can re-read stops being a state of mind and becomes a fact
of the world. The friction is uniform, around thirty seconds per
exchange, and it folds into routine after a week of practice.

The rule also applies to humans relaying numbers to other humans — an
unsourced count is just as evidentially null whether produced by an
agent or by a colleague. The agent simply produces them at higher
throughput, which makes the rule more visible.
